															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/marcuse" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1949481); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1949481&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610250346" alt="Marcuse" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1949481)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/marcuse" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1949481); return false;" >Marcuse</a></span> <span class="odate time_1430139506 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">27 Apr 2015 12:58</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2280288">
									

<p>I gave this one a downvote, and I feel like I should explain why I don't like what is probably going to be a well regarded tale.</p>
<p>The problem I have here is that this didn't make me feel anything. There's lots of crosslinked SCPs that are linked back to the original articles (which is a nice touch btw), but left me sort of looking at it like it felt a bit obvious? Like the presence of linked SCPs we recognise was sort of the impact, rather than what they do. This was especially true for me with the spider near the end. It just felt like another piece of work was being dangled in front of me in the hope that would elicit a reaction, and that dangling felt obvious to me while I was reading.</p>
<p>I found what was happening to be extremely hard to follow on first reading. It's obviously packed with action and stuff and SCPs, but that meant I spent the majority of the piece feeling more bewildered than entertained. This meant that the length of the piece started to drag for me, where I've read SCP articles that are possibly longer or in the same area and not experienced that.</p>
<p>By the end, I was rather confused, and I walked away from the piece feeling like something had happened, but I wasn't sure what. Other than that though, the piece was written in a way that was easy to read, and technically it's more than good.</p>

							</div>

								
					
