    <div class="post-container" id="fpc-2280345">
                      
		<div class="post" id="post-2280345">
		<div class="long">
			<div class="head">
									<div class="options">
						<a href="javascript:;" onclick="togglePostFold(event,2280345)" class="btn btn-default btn-small btn-sm">Fold</a>
					</div>
								<div class="title" id="post-title-2280345">
																		
															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/patrick-whelan" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2113745); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=2113745&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610250346" alt="Patrick Whelan" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=2113745)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/patrick-whelan" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2113745); return false;" >Patrick Whelan</a></span> <span class="odate time_1430145832 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">27 Apr 2015 14:43</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2280345">
									

<p>Ahhhhhh I have to give this a -1 as well, at this point, considering the people and the ambition behind this series there needs to be a higher level of execution than this.</p>
<p>It is a rare story that works with <em>a dozen</em> crosslinks, and this one isn't it. At least half of the SCPs could have been swapped with any number of other randomly selected SCPs and the story would be almost identical, and the ones that move the plot don't feel like they were selected for any reason more thoughtful than that they were first one that popped into the authors head when he was looking for McGuffin which could plausibly cause X event. You could rewrite this story a dozen times with a different set of SCPs each and every time and it could be kept nearly identical, that is a sign that these crosslinks didn't work.</p>
<p>Casual crosslinking does nothing but kill the pace of the story, instead of humming along through a really cool idea (Shirley in 2322!) I had to open a new tab every minute to remind myself what the SCP d'jour was, only to have it exit the story not two paragraphs later. If you dropped 6-8 of the crosslinks and just left them in as easter eggs (literally just get rid of the link) I think this story would move a lot better, but even then, this still has a weak opening, characters I still can't get myself to care about, and an underutilization of what should have been a great idea.</p>
<p>If this story had been written outside of the context of Resurrection I think it could have been so much better. Light being in this didn't add anything at all (it doesn't help that I find Light to be one of the most boring characters in this entire series so far), and I suspect the number of crosslinks was motivated at least partially by trying to fufilled the goal of Resurrection re-popularizing them. I just kept getting the feeling like this story was torn in two directions, telling a serious story about Shirley in 2322, or a Resurrection tale. The levity in the story also missed the mark a bit as well, again, it wasn't casual or serious enough, but in a weird middle ground where all the off-beat events, concepts, and phrasings that should normally be charming just felt awkward.</p>
<p>Is this bad? No, it isn't, but it did not draw me in, and it left me with a very real feeling that it missed the mark over and over again.</p>

							</div>

								
